<br>
Hissing out a quick incantation, he rooted Brutus just out of reach of the undead he had been charging, and gave out a soft sigh of relief.  Brutus, on the other hand, turned to Undeen angrily.  &quot;Wha are ya doin?!&quot;  His wolf turned on Undeen, snarling and about to leap.<br>
<br>
&quot;Two simple facts, Brutus.  Being a veteran warrior, and knowing there are at least three times as many Undead between here and the way out then you saw when you came in.  Were we to fight, we would die.  No questions asked.  Secondly, attacking your allies is NEVER prudent.&quot;  Undeen leveled a hard glare at Brutus and the pair stared off for multiple minutes.  Undeen's enstill spell wore off long before Brutus finally turned from Undeen's eyes when Undeen snarled, giving a flash of vampiric fangs.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alroigh....  So ya's one's dem, an' they's our allies.&quot;  Brutus sounded in no way pleased, but made a signal, forcing his wolf to calm and come to his side.<br>
<br>
Walking to the ground again, Brutus whispered harshly to Undeen.  &quot;You get us killed, an' oi'll haunt ya all through moi afterlife..&quot;  <br>
<br>
Undeen simply nodded acceptance and turned back to the spirit before him.  &quot;I apologies for his actions.  He did not realize our agreement.  I will speak with him more completely upon what is to happen here shortly.  First, I believe it best, with your permission, we find a place to rest, regroup, and prepare for the attacks to come.&quot;<br>
<br>
The long dead shamaness looked over at Brutus, her eyes somewhere between anger and jealousy.  Jealousy that he is a living shaman, and she isn't, most likely.  The undead are often jealous of the living.  &quot;Ssssee that you do jussst that, Lar'Tesssse.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nodding quickly, Undeen turned back to the group and motions for them to begin walking, seeking out a small house in the city.  Any house would do, really...<br>
<br>
