<br>
The barbarian thunked his spear butt to the ground once. &quot;Tha oak of Faydark,&quot; he thumped again. &quot;Tha frosts of Velious,&quot; **thunk** &quot;Tha wauters of Rathe,&quot; **thunk** &quot;Tha plains of Antonica,&quot; **thunkthunk** &quot;Tha swomps of Innothule...&quot; he let out three, mournful thunks, and hung his head, sweeping blue powder from a belt pouch. &quot;They've all felt my presence. They all feel it again...&quot; the powder swirled with the winds picking up in the abysmal structure. &quot;And now, they feel you as well.&quot;<br>
<br>
A luminescence poured forth from the spiral that weaved around the room, touching and wrapping around the party of five. Chattering sounds of the jungle swept across their ears, and the most vibrant colors stood out to their naked eyes. All senses heightened, all attributes amplified... &quot;The sp'rits deem ye worthy. We foight an' dai for ye. But ye must come outside with me fer a moment.&quot; Brutus put a fist to his heart, saluting the undead shamaness. She seemed indifferent to the gesture, which was better than the threatening look she gave at first...<br>
<br>
Past the stagnant pools and rotting walls, they made their way to the front of Old Torsis. &quot;Open the pow'r of yuir 'art...&quot; he muttered. From his pure, gentle heart, all the spirits that had joined him since his early days poured outwards, flowing freely from his massive body. Bats screeched and flew through the corporeal forms of his comrades, wolves were absorbed into their bodies, streaking lions and blurred bears danced around all about them- the shaman had done his work.<br>
<br>
Brutus himself felt super-charged with the spirits of the wilderness flowing through him most untamed than before; almost as if he could lift the entire Iksar army with one hand. A thought jolted him- &quot;Ayy. Remember that yuir not invincible now; merely strong. This is yuir pow'r unleashed, but ye ain't a god yet. Keep yuir 'ead.&quot; Luminescent animal-figures crowded in around the masses of thirsty undead. Natural and unnatural... who'da guessed?<br>
<br>
The barbarian opened his eyes again; he had amazing clairvoyance now, and could see farther and sharper, with less interferance than before! He wondered what powers the others had unlocked... No matter. He beamed, absolutely ecstatic, as he saw a tree limb bend down and cleave through a pair of Iksar necromancers. &quot;Undeen, ye blimy vampire,&quot; Brutus called. The heat of war made shimmering lines above his body. &quot;First blood is ours.&quot;<br>
<br>
He smirked. &quot;Good. And I'm no more a vampire than you are a wolf or tree.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tree? Brutus chuckled. &quot;Wot koind of tree? And couldja explain the teef deal then, eh?&quot; He tossed a spear to Nallu, and mouthed the words &quot;little brother&quot; at him. Maybe the wee man would be useful...? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uundeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Undeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/16/02 2:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ffantasystoriesforumfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10.topic&index=71>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Old Torsis</span><hr size=1> I absolutely beamed.  We were all going to stay, and the shaman was showing the power his kind was famous for.  A complete harnessing of spirit.  I continued to look over the area.  I couldn't see Iksar, but I knew Iksar.  They were out there.  They had come sooner then I had expected.  I was hoping at least for a horrible night's sleep first...  No matter.<br>
<br>
&quot;Family trait.  I'll explain more later, when we have a bit more time..&quot;<br>
<br>
There.  The trees and plants were the only things currently with the Iksar, and they were anchored to the ground.  A gravity flux it was.<br>
<br>
I raised my hands and began to chant out the spell.  I couldn't tell for sure what the others did, but I would suppose they readied themselves to fight, and die.  &quot;Unto rathe thou art brought, atraction hold thee down.  inverse this attraction, and from the home of Rathe thou shalt rise!&quot;<br>
<br>
The spell was triggered, and a small troop of Iksar could be seen, suddenly hurled up, slashed and impaled by branches on the way up, and again on the way down.  I don't think any of them servived.  They hadn't expected that.  They weren't expecting much resistance at all, it seems.  A grim smile came to my lips then.  &quot;First blood indeed.&quot;<br>
<br>
The drums suddenly flared to life all around us, and the hisses of dieing Iksar were eminating from every tree and bush.  And suddenly.  Finally.  It happened.  All at once, sleek, scaled heads rose, and they charged.<br>
<br>
We were going to die.<br>
