<br>
Not wishing to look any longer, Tani turns to the sky. It was empty just as it had always been. Today the heavens were painted a monotone gray that bled out onto the lands and crawl into your very being to bring it to the same melancholy color as it was. A brief smirk turned a corner of her lips up. Today was a good day for a funeral. Just as the gloomy world above begins to soak into Tani, something pounds against her foot. Slowly, she brings her chin back down. A lizard. It had rolled and it's head landed on her foot, its body sprawled out to her left. It was bleeding heavily and struggling with the last few breaths it would ever take. Tani let their eyes lock. Iksars weren't so bad... She found herself admiring the black orbs that glistened like oil staring back at her. A crystal droplet slipped from those beautiful reptile eyes and cascaded down its smoky gray scales. Iksars... cried? Its eyes leave hers and gaze towards the emptiness above. <br>
<br>
&quot;Cazzzac... for..forgive me&quot;<br>
<br>
Tani knew now, what this was. This was hope. This was the iksar’s attempt at bringing their beloved god back to them. This was not war; there were no enemies here. To them, they symbolized the one thing standing in the way of their god returning to them, the single thing stopping them for attaining their goals. How wrong they were. Tani was too young to know anything of how the world was before the gods, but she knew that her death, and the death of those with her, would not help return them to Norrath. This was the ignorant and blinding hope of the lizards, and this was death. Nothing would be gained today. Much would be lost. This was a good day for a funeral.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
Long she stood. Her mind lay still somewhere between consciousness and otherwise. Nothing attacked her. Perhaps because of her size, they did not see her. Or perhaps because all she did was stand. Her undisturbed state allowed her to stay as she was all the more longer. A scream. A cry. A noise of some sort broke the binds on her mind and woke her to reality. Almost frantically her eyes jump from thing to thing. The dead, the blood, the fighting, the incomprehensible amount of iksar marching their way... She had to get out. She had to. Something deep within her soul told her to run, but her body would not budge. If their god was anywhere in sight, he would have been smiling down on the iksar. Tani was paralyzed with fear. A burning, electrifying sensation burst from her shoulder and leaked through her entire arm. Just as quickly as the pain had come, it was gone again. What in Tunare's name... Now a tickle. On the back of her neck. Knowing nothing else to do but turn, Tani does so. Undeen! He was hurt... One of these filthy beasts had shot him with an arrow! Blood... There was blood... It stained his robe and drizzled down his arm. Blood. They drew his blood. She could almost hear her molars grinding against each other and a twinge fluttered her eyebrow. <br>
<br>
<br>
They. <br>
<br>
<br>
Were all. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Going. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
To die.<br>
<br>
<br>
Crystal blue eyes pierce the crowd of beasts that steadily increased despite the numbers that fell. Tani's slender fingers reach behind her and pull her daggers from her belt. They were all[/i] going to die... But which one first? Decisions, decisions... Tani heard a loud... 'meow' ? Spinning to her side she sees the feline-ish one sitting on his bum using his sword like a barrier to keep a rather grubby looking iksar from slicing him in two. How easy he made her choice. A devilish grin dances on her lips while she strolls over to the cat-man. She stands there a second, watching the beads of sweat form on his brow and the strain both him and the reptile had on their faces. Her grin diminishes into a snarly sort of grimace. Disgusting creature at her feet, Tani thinks its time for you to bleed. Twirling a dagger, she catches it and grips it firmly. First one should always be quick. After all, if you kill your opponent in a single strike, there is no need for a second. Tani thrusts the platinum blade through the skull of the cat-man's attacker. Pushing what little weight she had into her leg and down her foot, she kicks the brand new fountain she had just made off of the cat-man. She leaves her dagger in the tiny brain of the iksar and looks around. A dagger simply would not do! She needed something... bigger... Like that pretty sharp sword that savage looking iksar was using! Tani felt the great need for upgrade...<br>
